<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="5" type="phenology">
<paragraph pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Phenology.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="4" pageNumber="5">The species has been collected with flowers and fruits from November to February and with fruits only from January to February.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="5" pageNumber="6" type="etymology">
<paragraph pageId="5" pageNumber="6">
<pageBreakToken pageId="5" pageNumber="6" start="start">Etymology</pageBreakToken>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="5" pageNumber="6">
The specific epithet stems from the vernacular name takape (Guarani language). This word is used for a particular habitat characterised by a wooded savannah or open woodland (
<bibRefCitation author="Bertoni, MS" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" refId="B2" refString="Bertoni, MS, 1940. Diccionario Botanico Latino-Guarani y Guarani-Latino con un glosario de vocablos y elementos de la nomenclatura botanica. Editorial Guarani, Asuncion, 99-100." title="Diccionario Botanico Latino-Guarani y Guarani-Latino con un glosario de vocablos y elementos de la nomenclatura botanica. Editorial Guarani, Asuncion, 99 - 100." year="1940">Bertoni 1940</bibRefCitation>
). The word is also applied to small woody plants (i.e. subshrubs). This is based on the word 
<normalizedToken originalValue="takã">taka</normalizedToken>
(twig or branch) and the suffix 
<normalizedToken originalValue="‘pe’">'pe'</normalizedToken>
(short or dwarf). Both meanings fit the newly described species of 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Euphorbiaceae" genus="Manihot" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Manihot" order="Malpighiales" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">Manihot</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="5" pageNumber="6" type="conservation status">
<paragraph pageId="5" pageNumber="6">Conservation status.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="5" pageNumber="6">
A preliminary conservation assessment with the GeoCat Tool indicates that 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Euphorbiaceae" genus="M." higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="M. takape" order="Malpighiales" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="takape">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">M. takape</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be initially considered as Endangered, with an extent of occurrence of 1,887 km2 and an area of occupancy of 28 km2 (based on an UICN default cell width of 2 km). Furthermore, with only 5 locations known to this date and considering the high deforestation and land use changes in the Paraguayan Chaco (
<bibRefCitation author="Arevalos, F" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" publicationUrl="http://guyra.org.py/informe-deforestacion" refId="B1" refString="Arevalos, F, Ortiz, E, Baez, M, Benitez, C, Allegretti, L, Dure, A, 2018. Monitoreo Mensual del Cambio de Uso y Cobertura de la Tierra, Incendios y Variacion de la Cubierta de Aguas en el Gran Chaco Americano; Enero 2018. Guyra Paraguay. http://guyra.org.py/informe-deforestacion" title="Monitoreo Mensual del Cambio de Uso y Cobertura de la Tierra, Incendios y Variacion de la Cubierta de Aguas en el Gran Chaco Americano; Enero 2018. Guyra Paraguay." url="http://guyra.org.py/informe-deforestacion" year="2018">
<normalizedToken originalValue="Arévalos">Arevalos</normalizedToken>
et al. 2018
</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Cardozo, R" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" publicationUrl="http://guyra.org.py/paraquaria-2013/" refId="B3" refString="Cardozo, R, Palacios, F, Rodas, O, Yanosky, A, 2013. Cambio en la cobertura de la tierra del Gran Chaco Americano en el ano 2012. Paraquaria Natural 1(2): 43-49. http://guyra.org.py/paraquaria-2013/" title="Cambio en la cobertura de la tierra del Gran Chaco Americano en el ano 2012. Paraquaria Natural 1 (2): 43 - 49." url="http://guyra.org.py/paraquaria-2013/" year="2013">Cardozo et al. 2013</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.gloplacha.2008.12.009" author="Huang, G" journalOrPublisher="Global and Planetary Change" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" pagination="1 - 12" refId="B5" refString="Huang, G, Kim, S, Song, K, Townshend, JRG, Davis, P, Altstatt, A, Rodas, O, Yanosky, A, Clay, R, Tucker, CJ, Musinsky, J, 2009. Assessment of Paraguay's forest cover change using Landsat observations. Global and Planetary Change 67 (1-2): 1 - 12, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1016/j.gloplacha.2008.12.009" title="Assessment of Paraguay's forest cover change using Landsat observations." url="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.gloplacha.2008.12.009" volume="67" year="2009">Huang et al. 2009</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1007/s10584-014-1256-3" author="Mereles, F" journalOrPublisher="Climatic Change" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" pagination="55 - 71" refId="B12" refString="Mereles, F, Rodas, O, 2014. Assessment of rates of deforestation classes in the Paraguayan Chaco (Great South American Chaco) with comments on the vulnerability of forest fragments to climate change. Climatic Change 127 (1): 55 - 71, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1007/s10584-014-1256-3" title="Assessment of rates of deforestation classes in the Paraguayan Chaco (Great South American Chaco) with comments on the vulnerability of forest fragments to climate change." url="https://doi.org/10.1007/s10584-014-1256-3" volume="127" year="2014">Mereles and Rodas 2014</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Yanosky, A" journalOrPublisher="Systematic Botany" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" publicationUrl="http://guyra.org.py/paraquaria-2013/" refId="B21" refString="Yanosky, A, 2013. The challenge of conserving a natural Chaco habitat. Paraquaria Natural 1(1): 32-34. http://guyra.org.py/paraquaria-2013/" title="The challenge of conserving a natural Chaco habitat. Paraquaria Natural 1 (1): 32 - 34." url="http://guyra.org.py/paraquaria-2013/" year="2013">Yanosky 2013</bibRefCitation>
), the preliminary UICN category proposed for this species is Endangered B1ab(iii)+2ab(iii). It is worth mentioning that the type locality, known as 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">Parque Valle Natural</emphasis>
in Neuland, 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Boquerón">Boqueron</normalizedToken>
, is a private reserve of approximately 0.5 km2 that harbours a small population of the new species. The current conservation status of the remaining four locations is unknown. Further field observations and collections are strongly recommended to achieve a more conclusive conservation assessment.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
